postTitle:
#68130 I've started writing this confession several times and stopped myself, because I know there's no real point to it, but I guess I just want to say these things in whatever way I can.

I actually fell in love, I think for the very first time. Admittedly it's not real love, like when you totally surrender to the vulnerability of it because it's reciprocal, and might just be everything it could ever be. It's pretty obvious she's not interested in me. I know I'm lucky just because I can even be so delusional as to think that she might be interested - that I might be in her league. However close I might be to her feeling the same way about me, just the fact that I can have these daydreams and think they could come true is already a nice thing - I remember growing up and thinking I wouldn't be good enough for anyone at all, so things really could be a whole lot worse. But I've had her on my mind for such a long time, because this girl is so beautiful in every way, and I don't remember feeling quite like this about anyone for the longest time. I've thought of a million compliments for her, and my heart actually aches sometimes when I think about her. She has such a pretty laugh, and she's so graceful, so feminine, and so driven too, a really strong person and yet totally disarming in how beautiful she is. I mean, she's gorgeous, but it's her personality that makes her totally radiant. I'm amazed by how hard it is for me to accept reality when I want something this much. Mostly I'm happy to have this aching feeling though, to know what it's like to really feel so much tenderness for someone. It puts things into perspective, and gives me a little glimpse of the beautiful emotions that I could someday get lost in.

text: Third possibility is that they perceive themselves as excluded but they aren't really, in fact they are welcome.
postTitle:
#68058 Are you someone whose friends always seem to exclude you from things?

Have you ever thought about why they don't invite you? People don't do things without a reason. There are really only two scenarios, with two clear courses of action to take.

The first scenario is that this friend group is toxic and mean-spirited and exclude people from things for selfish/immature reasons that would persist regardless of your character. You should not be sad that they excluded you. In fact, you should be thanking your lucky stars that you dodged an entire hailstorm of bullets, and go and find some better friends.

The second scenario is that there is nothing obviously wrong with the friend group. They are relatively decent people, and they get along with each other fine and hang out all the time, just not with you. Have you really, deeply thought about why this might be? Think about it - why would an entire friend group exclude someone who is kind and fun to be around? Would *you* want to avoid someone who was kind and fun to be around? People do not do things (or consistently "forget" to invite someone) for no reason - there's ALWAYS a reason. Thus the only possibility is that you are unkind or unpleasant to be around, or both (usually there is a strong correlation between these traits). In this case, you should not find it unreasonable that your so-called friends don't include you in things (since you'd probably do the same thing to someone you didn't like, wouldn't you?). Instead, if your friend group is a group that you care about and want to keep your connections with, you should try to become a kinder and more pleasant person that people would naturally want to hang out with - you can't really force anyone to want to be with you. It may take some time for them to notice, so you will need to be patient - of course, there is also no guarantee that they'll ever notice, but it's not like you've lost anything by becoming a kinder person. The other possibility (and by far the easiest thing for you to do) is that you don't change at all - in this case, you should be prepared to continue being excluded from things, and you should no longer be upset about it - after all, it's your choice.

Tl;dr - if none of your friends want to hang out with you, either your friends all have problems, or you have problems. If your friends all have problems, then find better friends. If you have problems, then be a better person.

Some notes: I've noticed that for a great deal of people (especially for people who post complaints on this page), whenever something doesn't go their way, they immediately think that it's everyone's problem but their own. This is a mindset that doesn't promote introspection or self-improvement, displays a lack of wisdom, and leads to things like MIT Confessions posts about problems that have very obvious (though not necessarily easy) solutions, if one took only a few minutes to think about it first.

My mom was my biggest supporter. She never missed a soccer game or math competition. postTitle: #66379 Is it normal for your body to burn up like a furnace every night? Apparently it's so bad that my partner will wake up sweating buckets in the middle of the night if we try to share a blanket and end up choosing to sleep on the floor. I had some doubts since I don't feel hot or sweat at all through the night, but I've been taking my temp right when I wake up and hot damn I really do heat up like the desert in summer. It doesn't seem healthy to essentially be running a mid-grade fever every night, but I don't feel sick at all and this has apparently been a thing all my life. I've been googling it and warming up at night seems to be a thing, but not to this extreme. Now that I'm paying attention, I always seem to wake up with my veins bulging and skin a little bit red like I've just worked out. Will I be forever sleeping by myself due to my stupid high nighttime body temperature? Was I cursed by a witch as a baby to always be objectively hot but feel super cold?

On the topic of ghosting that has been on here a bit, I can understand why my ghoster feels uncomfortable with talking to me, but it truly destroys your mind as the person who gets ghosted. For someone who suffers immensely from social isolation and is so afraid of people and scaring them away, getting ghosted absolutely ruins everything, especially when it's someone that you cannot simply avoid. Things would be so much simpler and way less painful if you have a mature conversation about things, rather than avoiding it all together. To my ghoster, I do not blame you. I have never once been mad at you. I just want to properly talk things through so that this misunderstanding can peacefully stop. I lost a friend, and it fucking sucks. I feel like a monster, a big bad wolf in a cave that people avoid despite the internal hurt. To ghosters, PLEASE understand that the emotional implications might be incredibly damaging. PLEASE reach out before it might be too late.

You can say this person is inconsiderate and say they are not good for them, but saying it is childish is an oversimplification of the wide range of situations people can experience.
postTitle:
#66145 Ghosting is a sign of immaturity and is extremely toxic under nearly all circumstances.

I lost someone who I thought was a really great friend. Met in classes and psetted and studied together to endure the grind of courses while cracking jokes here and there to brighten eachothers day up. We would even nonpset hang out occasionally if we weren’t busy with work. Kept in contact over the summer and talked about our internships and how things were going until suddenly, they started to not respond. Asked about how classes were going this time around, and no message back. Asked if they needed a pset buddy and no message back. Asked if they were OKAY in general and needed anything and no message back. Check socials and ive been unfollowed and unfriended on them all.

Why do people ghost without atleast telling the other person why? I know everyone is going through stuff, but why not at the minimum just say you need time alone or cannot be friends anymore or whatever? How am I supposed to now NOT think it was because of me? We are literally in the same school so of course I see you and you see me but then you walk by with your friends seemingly happy but dont even verbally recognize me. We were just friends, and I felt like we did great helping eachother out and checking up on one another, but dang this feels cruel. I would never do that to someone so why do that to me? postTitle:
#67907 tldr; if your parents pay your tuition, stop repeatedly saying you are poor.

There's this person who keeps on saying they are poor and that they have no money. As a FLI, when they told me this, I assumed they were on financial aid. But then this person told me they pay full tuition and their mom is a doctor (who gets paid a lot). This person cosplaying as poor isn't offensive per se, but it is rather out of touch. Just because you have a limited budget for whatever reason does not make it okay to try garner empathy or sympathy. You are incredibly privileged to never have been unhoused or on food stamps or worry about having enough food or paying for a bus ticket back home or helping your family financially with bills.

For anyone who is in contact with their parents and whose parents are wealthy, you may have a limited budget because you don't want to depend on your parents (which is valid!). But it is incredibly tone deaf to say you are poor when in the worst case scenario, you do have some semblance of a safety net when it comes to money. Low income students don't even have that. In many cases, low income students ARE the financial safety net for their families.

postTitle: #66155 So the craziest thing has been happening recently. The crazy thing is this: I feel fine. I don't feel sad. I don't feel intense-self-loathing. I don't feel exhausted, angry, like an imposter, or like I'm not enough. These feeling are usually a near constant and yet after Thanksgiving break I don't have them. I haven't been doing better in classes--in fact I am still struggling in a couple--i haven't been sleeping that much more, I haven't had a radical life change or started medication, and yet I feel fine, maybe even good?! It's so weird for me to feel this way, to experience this place with a positive filter on in my brain and I can't figure out what exactly put that filter there. Maybe it was the chance to recharge with family for a couple days? I almost feel guilty. Am I allowed to be ok when I know so many others are struggling right now? I have friends--not many but enough--and family who care about me, I have a personal project I enjoy and find stimulating, and I don't have to worry about having food to eat or a warm place to sleep. This is enough, I am enough, and I feel good. For the first time in my 3 years at MIT, I feel good. This place has brought me to my lowest lows but also some of my highest highs. Before the break I was questioning if this place was worth it. If the intense stress, sleep deprivation, and struggle were ever going to be worth experiencing. I don't know the answer to that, if the darkness is worth the moments of light. But for now, in this moment of light, I'm going to cherish what I have and remember I am ok.

But from the outside, it looks picture perfect. Hell, most of the time, it’s perfect on the inside too. But sometimes I let my thoughts wander, often prompted by tiny queues that would otherwise be forgotten… everything always feels just a little off, but I can’t put my finger on it. I love everyone in it, but part of me feels like we’re just a house of cards waiting to fall- and I don’t know how to be prepared for that, or if I’m just being anxious over nothing. How do other people deal with this? This is such a nebulous question but it’s an intrusive concept and I just can’t stop thinking about it recently :(

postTitle:
#67931 I know there's a huge activation energy to moving out! but consider: mit housing is NOT market price, and imo was never intended to be. essay incoming: 

obviously you won't find super cheap housing right next to campus because a lot of it is mit-owned or commercial but for the cost of a tier ii single ($1450/month assuming you're here for iap), you can get a *very nice* room with 1-3 other people within 10 min by bus. for the cost of a tier ii single + dining plan ($1900+/month during the semester) you can even get a relatively spacious studio in central/harvard and still have extra $200/month budget for food. this might not seem like a great deal but remember the 125 plan only covers an average of one meal a day, plus from personal experience you'll spend way less on uber eats since you'll have a cleaner kitchen shared with less people and you'll no longer live in a relative food desert. and if you're willing to deal with other people in a fsilg or live farther away, you can save even more. 

now, why is mit housing so expensive? first, because they deal with a lot of things for you. you don't have to spend 50+ hours apartment hunting and going through a broker, or have to furnish your own room, or call or hunt down your management company every time you need something, there's a convenient atlas request system, there's security workers to make sure the building is safe and let you in when necessary, and at least in tier ii dorms most of the appliances and electric systems are reasonably updated, i.e. you might not have really sketchy electric stoves where each burner needs to be turned just so in order to actually heat up. not to mention that building services even cleans your bathrooms for you. that's a lot of people they're paying to hopefully make your life a little easier. also, housing revenue margins are fairly slim because of maintenance costs. mit estimates a total $1.5b campus maintenance backlog (> $100/sq ft), a lot of which is student housing, and they keep building new dorms precisely because so many undergrad and grad students want to live on campus these days (part of which might be 2000s-era pushback against frat and alternative cultures, but anyway). aside from space/capacity issues, you're paying for these (intended) quality of life improvements and maybe the experience of mit dorm culture? I understand it's sad to leave that behind but ultimately if you'd rather not pay the premium and are able to dedicate a bit of bandwidth each week to your housing, consider not living on campus/shouldering mit's construction burdens and finding cheaper ways to be part of the mit community.

#66541 I'm so fucking lonely. 
Winter break has not even started yet.
I'm sick. I have one more final. And it's been so long since I've been home.
Maybe it's the fever making me feel this way.
It keeps happening. I feel good. Alright. Hopeful. Positive. 
And then, BAM! 
NO MORE. Only sadness remains. Yearning for love. Care. Attention. I wanna cry so badly. It pains me. I wake up in the middle of the night, wondering if I'm me. I freak out, touch my face, and breathe heavily for a few moments, before convincing myself I am me. 
I am in pain.

text:
If I still lived in Boston, I'd invite you to come hang out with me. But unfortunately I'm on the other side of the Atlantic now, so that makes hangouts a little difficult. But I'm happy for you to DM me, if you ever find yourself in a place where you just need someone to talk to.

And yes: The fever, sickness, and stress from exams aren't helping. Those are all things that can make anxiety and depression kick into overdrive--and, for added fun, those two tend to mutually reenforce each other. Part of why you feel crappy is, well, you feel crappy. It's really hard for your mind to be happy when your body isn't. If you can, I recommend when you get those really overwhelming feelings to try to get up and move: Go for a walk outside, if you can. Dance badly (or well, if you're more talented than i am!) to music you like. Heck, just sway in place, if that's all you've got in you.

And hang in there. One more final, you've got this.

MIT has always been building something, somewhere. From 2013-2017 or so MIT Nano was just an enormous hole in the ground and the entire "outfinite" felt largely inaccessible for the latter half of its construction. 

Since "in the last three years" is what we're working with here,  Hayden was renovated, Kendall Square 4 (a replacement for Eastgate) has opened, 314 Main and the new Museum, The Polaroid building was torn down and replaced, Burton Conner was renovated, KSQ1 (housing) opened, there's a new welcome center and "campus gateway" as they're calling it, but the new subway station and retail center are technically not MIT and still under construction. 

Idk what else but there's always SOMETHING being done and this is not an exhaustive list. Just because you don't walk by it every day doesn't mean it doesn't matter to someone. I think just two of these projects I listed exceed like ~500 housing units for grad students.

postTitle: #66070 I am so sick of applying to jobs and interviewing. I feel like I've tried everything over the past four months, from meeting with career services, grinding out dozens of practice problems, and asking people for advice. But everything I've learned and achieved at this university during the past three and a half years goes to waste as soon as I'm not able to solve the interviewer's math riddle that has nothing to do with the actual job. I feel so worthless not being able to provide for myself or my family. I feel like such a failure.

text:
You're not alone, stay on the grind and hang in there. Job hunting sucks for everyone and when there are a hundred people applying for every job, we're all met with a sea of rejections before we find one. Reading that back it sounds less encouraging than I meant it to be, but it's true.
Unless you happen to meet the right people with connections. You're not a failure, I think even a lot of us cruft have sent out a hundred resumes and not gotten a callback at some point. I know I have. It sounds like you're getting interviewed which is a great sign, just the fact that they called you in for interviews shows you're better than 95% of the candidates who applied. Especially in this economy, it's competitive out there in tech and even in better times, there are floods of resumes for a single position. Very few of them get an interview at all.
Job hunting just sucks, it's hundreds of applications, a handful of interviews and if you're lucky some connections who can recommend you. It always feels like you're not getting anywhere as you see 99% of your work disappearing into the void and almost nobody has the decency to send a rejection email anymore. But you only need one good offer letter and when you get it, everything suddenly changes really fast to be good. 
Also, these interviews are like exams, they're a poor judge of how successful you'll actually be in the future. Getting an F on one doesn't say anything about your worth. Also, if you get a B+ and someone else gets an A-, you'll still get rejected and never hear how close you were. 
Good luck, hang in there. I know getting rejected sucks and unfortunately job hunting involves tons of rejections. You'll make it eventually, just keep scrolling to the top of the newly posted positions and apply to like five or ten of them every day. You do have what it takes, it's just a competitive market. You're gonna be OK.

Where it all starts is by voicing our opinions and gaining support from others.

postTitle:
#67716 Course 9 here:
I generally love course 9. It is run really well, the content is interesting, and you can kind of put in however much work you want. However, 9.40 can go suck its own dick. 
First of all, it is a class that is literally computational cognition. It is a 6-9 class. Yet it is not required for course 6-9 and is instead only required for course 9 AND the course 9 minor. This leads to most people in the class complaining about it since none of us want to code and very few 6-9s taking it because of what they hear about it. 
Second of all, the content is ridiculous. I am a double major in 18, and the content that we are learning is very much based in math, except that they don't have time to teach us the math, and try to get away with giving us a surface level understanding, then asking us to code it. It is nigh on impossible to code something that you don't understand. There should be many math prereqs to this class or it should be a grad class. The ideas are not difficult, they are just trying to do far too much and thus only teach us surface level anything but the psets and exams require an actual understanding of not just the ideas, but the math that the ideas are based upon. One of our problems on the first exam was to derive the 3D diffusion constant. 
Third, although the exams are open note and we have two hours to do them, they are 17 pages long. Image a 17 page long PSET. I don't care if that's open note but you're not gonna finish it in two hours. They say the questions are straightforward, but again, that is based on the assumption that we understand the math basis that they skim over in class. It's not even that the math is too difficult, it's just that each new concept requires a new math concept that should take at least 3 lectures to teach just the math. And it is evident that the professors themselves do not really understand the math as they are not good at answering specific questions about it such as edge cases, derivations, etc and instead tell us not to worry about it. We are expected to develop an understanding of something without ever being shown where it comes from. 
The psets are often unclear in their questions and so are the exams, and the two are completely different so there is no real method of studying for the exams by doing the PSETS. It feels like the coding portion of this class is entirely unnecessary particularly considering it is not a 6-9 requirement. Things in this class are not explained well.

text:
anecdotally it's possible for someone's efc to be their entire household income if their family technically holds non-liquid assets that are worth more (e.g. you live in a more expensive zip code), because the fafsa calculation weighs in assets and where you live but might not count special family circumstances. this is true even if the family makes <$70k. please keep this in mind when hearing about others efcs. 

also, $120k income families in a high cost of living area might have $80-90k after taxes and mortgage get no financial aid so the $70k sticker cost is still substantial. not saying these families live in poverty or should claim the label poor, but it can still be a substantial financial strain especially if there are other family circumstances. we can all complain about the cost of college op

text:
that's a great question! tl;dr gravity also moves with the speed of light (as predicted by einstein's theory of general relativity), so if the sun were to hypothetically suddenly disappear, the earth would continue to orbit the "old" sun for 8 minutes (the time it takes for light to reach the earth). Since 2017, we even have experimental evidence that gravity indeed travels with the speed of light, as we have detected gravitational wave sources that we have simultaneously seen with a telescope.

note: The hypothetical situation where the sun suddenly disappears is not very realistic, as mass cannot just suddenly disappear, I guess you could just move the mass away from the earth very fast (up to the speed of light). You could also convert mass to energy (E=mc^2), but as far as I know, energy also exerts gravitational force, so I don't think it would affect gravity unless you move it.

#68051 Post nut clarity question here, but is gravity faster than light? I guess I’ve been thinking of this absurd hypothetical situation where the Sun suddenly disappears. Ignoring the obvious death to us lol, wouldn’t we/the planet feel the change in gravitational force before we see that there is longer light from the sun? Or do forces like gravity and light just propagate at the same speed? 
This has been killing me, so any answers would be appreciated! (Please be nice too; I’ve only taken GIR physics 🥺🥺)

text:
The usual rule is that anything that would convey *information* faster than the speed of light (in a vacuum) is against the rules.

So that would mean the gravity propagation is limited.

This is a pretty good rule of thumb. If something is "traveling" faster than the speed of light can't be used to convey information at that speed, then it might well be fine. 

For example, if you had a very big whiteboard very far away and you moved the point of a laser pointer across it, the dot might be moving faster than the speed of light but that's fine because this fact will not allow you to convey information faster than the speed of light.

#66124 hey guys! does anyone the key differences between 6.141, 6.800, and 6.832 

(does it overlap too much to take more than one of them)
(also which one should I take help)

text:
They're all pretty different, to my understanding! I've taken 6.832 and am taking 6.800.  6.832 and 6.800 are maybe somewhat similar in that they both are taught by Prof Tedrake, but 6.832 focuses much more on dynamics and their control (Think about controlling a humanoid!). 6.800 focuses on all of the different software components of a robotic manipulation system. They overlap quite little in the concepts that are taught.

To my knowledge, 6.141 is quite different from both, where you work in teams to get a real robot to do things. I think you probably won't be working with an underactuated system nor manipulators, but of course a lot of the techniques are still relevant.  

I love 6.832 and 6.800 and Prof Tedrake is great! Take them both! One is offered in the spring, and one in the fall.

6.141 may be a better choice if you want to see a lot of the different parts that go into building a robot? Probably read the syllabus to all of them to get a sense of what goes into all of these classes in more detail!
postTitle:
#66124 hey guys! does anyone the key differences between 6.141, 6.800, and 6.832 

(does it overlap too much to take more than one of them)
(also which one should I take help)

text:
Former TA for 6.141 here (also taken Underactuated and Manipulation):
They're all pretty different. 6.141 is very hands on. Students are assigned groups of 4-5 and get a fancy robot racecar to program. Assignments take 1-2 weeks and tend to culminate in a team final report and presentation (class is CI). The labs cover things like basic control, localization, perception, and planning. I'd say the most important thing is that you have programming experience with Python-- we don't really assume any robotics background.

Underactuated and Manipulation are both more research-focused, culminating in an open-ended research project for both. Each assignment usually has a few programming and a few theoretical questions. Manipulation focuses on perception, control, planning etc for robot arms (for the most part), while Underactuated talks more about robot locomotion. Latter class starts more on the theoretical control side before going into specific underactuated systems, like humanoids and cheetahs and stuff. There are a few topic overlaps between these two classes and 6.141, but the domains in which the topics are applied tend to be very different. Additionally, I found that Prof. Russ Tedrake talks a lot more about more "researchy" algorithms and approaches in his classes, whereas 6.141 covers more "standard," long-standing approaches (though I think we usually end on some funky ML lectures at the end).

But yes, definitely take all three! If you've got more questions, feel free to message me as well! :D

postTitle: #67736 Genuinely confused about people who are interested in research and have absolutely zero interest in learning to code. It's totally fine if you don't want to to be a software engineer. But just because you're not doing software engineering doesn't mean coding is useless to you. Consider course 9. Let's say you just want to learn about brains. You're not interested in AI shenanigans or focusing on data science or anything like that, just brain. You can research the brain without needing to code right? Wrong. How do you think all those computer experiments exist? You're gonna be coding them up yourself. How do you think people analyze data? Make pretty graphs? Sure, there are non-coding tools out there but people are mostly gonna be doing it with code, because it's way more flexible and arguably easier than learning a new GUI tool for every analysis you want to run. Maybe you're committed to using experiments that people have already created and are ready-to-go. Then you have to come up with some novel analysis if you want to make a new discovery, and that ain't gonna happen with your run of the mill preprogrammed analytic tools. Maybe you only apply to labs with dedicated software engineers who will do all the heavy coding for you. But if you're not coding your own stuff, you won't understand how it actually works. You won't be able to answer specific questions. Every time you want to make a change you have to play a telephone game with the software engineer and it might take a while before they get around to it. No matter what, you end up having to learn how to code anyways, at least a little bit, enough to run analyses and know what's going on.

text: It’s a brilliant system to allocate educational opportunities and resources in proportion to someone’s height.
postTitle: #67812 Biggest culture shock after moving to an ivy for grad school: the range of human sizes. MIT has no real focus on athletics. There are no people recruited primarily as athletes. Very Good athletes are not just hard workers, but also have extremely suitable body types for their chosen sport, which can range from tiny and compact to 7 feet tall. Thus, at MIT, the sizes of humans are relatively uniform. Yes, there are short people and tall people, but encountering someone who is extremely short or extremely tall is exceedingly rare. In Ivies, which do specifically recruit athletes, there are more extreme and specialized body types. I've seen and interacted with a lot more undergrads who are shockingly short or shockingly tall. Seriously, at MIT I've never once encountered someone who was so tall they sparked instinctual terror in me (for context, I am a woman who is the exact average American height). But I TA a class now, and I've already run into several undergrads who give me this feeling. Like, people who are just physically so huge it awakens my fight or flight mode. I feel like I expected a lot of the cultural differences I encountered between MIT and an Ivy, but this one truly takes the cake.

text:
I got over 50 rejections my senior year. In my fraternity we used to hang them outside our rooms. Everyone gets rejected and the more jobs you apply to the more you get rejected. But it only takes one.

1) Talk to the careers office and ask for help.
2) use the alumni database and find some alums at companies your interested in (or even just the field) and ask for advice
3) The career office isn't the only source of jobs. Post your resume on job boards.

We've all been there. You're still smarter and better educated than 99% of the population. It may seem daunting now but you will be ok.

postTitle: #66501 People with chronic pain: any advice to navigate MIT while dealing w the pain? I feel like I’m going crazy and have to be careful to not downplay my pain

text:
I’d really suggest reaching out to a healthcare provider who can help you navigate your chronic pain in the context of your study/work. I’m sorry you feel a pressure to downplay your pain and that you’re finding it challenging! 

Here are a few things I found helpful. Make sure there are people who are readily available that you can reach out to for medical and mental support and/or to vent to when you need it (I found MIT medical really helpful). Build allowances into your work/study and social plans to focus on self care in case you need it (even if you don’t think you will right now). Try not to get swept up in drinking from the fire hose and ignore signs you need to slow down. Make supervisors that you trust aware of your challenges and ask for their support in planning around them. Try and celebrate your achievements even while you acknowledge the limitations your health puts upon you:  it’s no small thing to be at MIT while experiencing chronic pain. You rock, and I hope it gets easier soon.

text: Since you mentioned that 70% of the C-suite in your company are alums from Stanford/MIT, I wonder if leadership is biased in promoting MIT folks over alums from other schools. I would also question the system of promotions, as not everyone wants to be a manager. It’s nice to have these privileges, but we should fight to eliminate bias in the workplace. If I was promoted over someone more competent due to MIT, I’d feel horrible. You mentioned giving back. Perhaps that means helping your colleagues get the salaries that they deserve.
postTitle:
#66389 As a recent MIT alum, I feel incredibly fortunate to be working for a non-tech company with global reach and a revenue north of $25 billion, the kind that most of the students here would just gloss over. I was never someone special during my time here and when I graduated I felt uncertain about my future in comparison to my peers. But now, I have been promoted quickly, as did many of my peers from prestigious schools like Stanford and Carnegie Mellon. People who attended slightly less than elite universities like the University of Michigan, Georgia Tech, and Purdue, on the other hand, were not so lucky. Many of them are either languishing in lower positions or have been laid off during the current recession.

 The work at this company is incredibly easy; it does not exceed the demands placed upon me by MIT as a junior, which admittedly is still a high bar all considered, and I never work more than 30 hours a week. It's almost criminal how much simpler my time here at this non-tech company is, considering that I make about double what my peers from Georgia Tech get with just ~4 years of experience. This is despite the fact that they work much longer hours. I believe a non-trivial portion of this is due to the company being dominated by MIT alumni who have gone on to become McKinsey alums and that 70% of the C-suite in my company are undergraduate alums, from either Stanford or MIT.

If you’re anything like how I was during my time as an MIT student, this post will likely bring a tremendous sense of relief - but that relief will be quickly overshadowed by a heavy wave of guilt. We must not forget our privilege in this day and age: an MIT degree, particularly from Course 6, still serves as a coveted ‘golden ticket’ to the upper echelons of American society. There are only around a thousand humans in the world that get the opportunities every year in this planet inhabited by billions. Although the current recession has undoubtedly caused immense distress for many, for many MIT alum, it is merely a brief challenge.

With this in mind, I implore you to think of ways in which you can give back to the community that has given you so much. It is likely that you will likely gain far more from this institution than you will ever give in return despite the less-than-idea food and the occasional rodent. It may be difficult to have this outlook now, but your future self will be grateful for keeping things in the right perspective.

I believe a non-trivial portion of this is due to the company being dominated by MIT alumni who have gone on to become McKinsey alums and that 70% of the C-suite in my company are undergraduate alums, from either Stanford or MIT.

If you’re anything like how I was during my time as an MIT student, this post will likely bring a tremendous sense of relief - but that relief will be quickly overshadowed by a heavy wave of guilt. We must not forget our privilege in this day and age: an MIT degree, particularly from Course 6, still serves as a coveted ‘golden ticket’ to the upper echelons of American society. There are only around a thousand humans in the world that get the opportunities every year in this planet inhabited by billions. Although the current recession has undoubtedly caused immense distress for many, for many MIT alum, it is merely a brief challenge.

With this in mind, I implore you to think of ways in which you can give back to the community that has given you so much. It is likely that you will likely gain far more from this institution than you will ever give in return despite the less-than-idea food and the occasional rodent. It may be difficult to have this outlook now, but your future self will be grateful for keeping things in the right perspective.

text:
If it's any consolation, i always struggled the most in the classes for my major. I failed a few classes, in my undergrad and in grad school, and i got turned down by quite a few internships along the way. It all worked out. 

If you took three classes and worked as hard as you could and still didn't get above a B in any of them...that means you took three *hard* classes, all at the same time, and you worked really hard, and you did well. Try not to be too tough on yourself, you're doing fine.

This is going to sound trite, but somebody said it to me once when i needed to hear it, and it stuck with me: If you could do 100% all the time, then 100% wouldn't be exceptional; by definition, it'd be average. *Nobody's* average is 100%.

text:
I don't deign to know what ADT is like nowadays, as I am literally THE cruftiest of ADT cruft. I just wanted to chime in to validate OP and #66153 in feeling like exec is cliquey. I don't particularly like the connotation of that word, as there is an implication of purposeful exclusivity and boundary; however, it would be silly to not admit that a sense of exclusivity *does* exist, by the very nature of it being an executive board. They literally spend hundreds of hours together every semester planning showcases/covers/events behind closed doors, in a process that most members do not see and cannot participate in. Folks on exec are probably more likely to be upperclassmen who have had more time in ADT overall (and therefore more time to find a friend group). They also are, by nature of being exec, individuals who have purposefully dedicated a large chunk of their time and energy into running a crazy huge student organization. When you are in a group of like-minded people, who are also crazy enough to do hundreds of hours of extracurricular service for free, who have had the time to bond through some pretty tough challenges... yeah, you ARE going to feel particularly close to them. And to folks on the outside, yes this DOES feel very exclusionary. I don't think the exclusion is on purpose, and I know when I was on exec we made every effort to do dance bonding events, impromptu boba runs/restaurant outings, I invited the whole team to parties at my apartment (I'll leave you to ponder the size of the team or the size of my apartment at the time).

I don't think it's for lack of want to get to know you better. What exec group doesn't want to feel close to their members, to feel like they're doing a good job supporting a student organization they clearly care about? But ADT is HUGE nowadays, and by that nature it is definitely difficult, both for exec and for members to feel connected and embedded. I do believe most people eventually find their own place, and encourage newbies to try another semester or two before writing it off entirely. Usually folks will find their stride by their 2nd or 3rd semester when you're more familiar with how things run and who's who. Also, I don't know if y'all still have adt-spam, but if that still exists then I'd encourage you to just send out messages asking if folks want to join you for events/shenanigans/gaming/what have you.

text:
i don't mean to be tailing all the adt-cliqueyness confessions, and to be clear i don't speak on behalf of a single person besides myself (and /especially/ not adt exec, for whom i suspect i am prolly just creating a smol headache). BUT.

OP (and other OP), i am not trying to dismiss your feelings about cliqueyness, but i guess i am saying there is no actual such a thing as "cliqueyness".

you seem to be saying that "adt exec/leadership is cliquey, and this makes adt unwelcoming and non-inclusive". well, what does it mean for adt exec to be cliquey, exactly? do you expect a group of people who spend a lot of time sharing the work of running an organization and maintaining a community to not become close friends with one another? do you expect people who are friends to... treat people who are not already their friends as openly and closely as they treat their friends? do you expect people to perform a social aesthetics of leadership at the expense of their personal social lives? i want you to really ask yourself: does "cliquey" mean anything besides "is a group of friends" && "has social status"?

you also say that adt is the biggest dance group on campus while simultaneously saying it is non-inclusive. what does that mean? how can both of those things be true? adt holds massive auditions that take like 25 people 20+ hours each to run, and accepts, tbh, more people than can comfortably fit in practice rooms. as an organization it is constantly taking action to allow for more members to join (like lowering the cap for number of dances per member). what would make it more inclusive and welcoming? in particular, what, beyond ppl performing a certain social aesthetics of leadership? i am pretty sure most members of adt leadership, like most members of adt, like most people at MIT, are introverts. what sort of social /work/ do they need to do to absolve themselves of the scarlet C for "cliquey"?

(as a side note, you mention that "it would not be a problem if it were a cliquey friend group". smaller organizations basically /are/ just "cliquey" friend groups—adt leadership is only more notable in this regard /because/ the organization is more inclusive and welcoming and has more members!!!)

i understand that is unpleasant to not be a part of a group that has social status in your life or community, and which therefore features prominently in your social awareness. but i also think it's important to recognize this feeling for what it is: envy. i'm sure there are all sorts of things adt could do to be /even more welcoming/ but i am very suspicious about pinning blame on its leadership being "cliquey", whatever that means.

here are a few relevant reads related to the point i'm trying to make about social groups and in-group envy:

- the five geek social fallacies; an ancient blog post about how negative social experiences can warp our understanding of how social groups "should work": https://plausiblydeniable.com/five-geek-social-fallacies/

- envy, by contrapoints; a lengthy video essay on recognizing envy and moving past it through, i guess, a sort of ecstatic sense of self: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aPhrTOg1RUk

(as you can see i am sort of a zealot about "cliqueyness" not being real. but hopefully some of these thoughts are informative... if not for OP then for someone out there.)

postTitle: #68013 I feel like MIT has turned me into a master of banana-eating. I have a whole technique an everything. Instead of biting off chunks of banana and getting slimy banana teeth, peel the banana inch by inch and bite-size pieces will break off cleanly. You can do this with your mouth or your fingers, if you're feeling extra fresh n fancy. I peel the banana from the "handle", always. This is because the peelability of the handle bit indicates banana ripeness. If you struggle, the banana isn't ready. If it comes off too easily, the banana is overripe and not fit for immediate consumption and should be carefully carried back to the dorm for use in banana bread. Also, leaving a little bit of peel at the very end will allow you to break off the banana right before the weird hard bit at the end. I also swear by splitting the banana peel into 3 pieces, as this minimizes the extra peel strings that sometimes get stuck to the banana. I've also become a total banana snob. I now only eat perfectly yellow bananas with no green patches or spots. Sometimes if I'm feeling funky I shine a blacklight on the bananas to make sure there's no programmed cell death showing on the peel, indicating overripeness. I fear for my future when I will inevitably have to return to purchasing subpar bananas from the grocery store and suffering through green patches and dark spots on my bananas.

text: I am so sad that MIT's banana culture (pun intended) developed after I left.

text: Coming from another country and also being part of a low income family was never so apparent to me until my time at MIT. You're right, we don't get to go on fancy boat rides in Europe, but hey, there's another face to it. You made it here on your own merit with the limited resources we had. No one will ever take that away from you. You'll be the change in your family and you will bring great success and prosperity to your future one. I can tell you it turns around. After a lot of work and perseverance, I obtained an internship that will allow me to earn more in a summer than my mom makes in a semester. And I'm so excited to help her with her expenses and finally be able to give back everything that she gave to me, even when money was lacking. Don't forget about what your family has done for you, and let them be an inspiration for your own resilient story. Money and success will come as a byproduct, you got it!
postTitle: #66483 coming from a low income family is really giving me an immense emotional distress from time to time. i try to ignore the privileges that my rich friends are so entitled to and be positive and get the most out of this education and the decent living that my family has just enough to provide me with. but i trembled and felt so helpless when seeing those kids going to fancy resorts with their families for vacation while for me, buying a flight ticket home would mean 3 months of even tighter living budget. idk man i get so sad and depressed sometimes because of this and just want to grow up and earn a lot of money

text: I was so busy working and studying that I had no time to compare my situation to others. Comparing yourself is a recipe for unhappiness. Know that you are not alone in being a poor student surrounded by wealthy people. If you focus on studying and achieving, you won’t be poor for long. Focus on all the good you do have. You are at MIT, so you are positioned to have a bright future.

text:
As someone who has gotten involved in the guild this year and has been having an amazing time, I cannot recommend it enough. The people are just so nice and welcoming. And I totally get feeling a little scared, I also felt that before my first game (LARPing felt like one of those things I'd call "intimidatingly quirky") but that fear was gone almost instantly when I started playing. Feel free to DM me if you have any questions.

And as others have said, I've also never heard of someone being bullied over the Assassins' Guild. As Dasha said, most stuff you can do at MIT can probably fall under “the kind of thing that people got bullied for in high school.”

text: Assassins Guild is basically my favourite thing I have going on at MIT right now. I only joined this IAP and I just can only wish I joined sooner. It's a type of story-telling you really get through no other medium with people who will commit to the acting as much as you do. You're at MIT, people are mature (and nerdy) enough to not bully others. The game that ran over IAP we still talk about months later because it just has so much story potential and the memories I formed with my new friends here I'll never forget.

text:
Hey there! I'm an MIT alum from 2010, and I did Guild during and after my college years. I still participate even now, 13 years later! It's a wonderful place to meet people both your age and older, learn how to write larps, play a lot of cool games, and be encouraged in your hobbies. There is not a culture of pushing down larpers at MIT. Guild is welcoming and encouraging, in my experience.

I hope you'll give it a try!

postTitle:
#66372 How do you write a good birthday message for a friend you have a serious crush on, but will never admit to her that you have the crush because you know you will be rejected and you (at least) never want the friendship to ever go away? 😭

I've tried to make this one crush stop for the last year, but have been wholly unsuccessful. Even when I try to think of her imperfections. Any advice on how to stop having a crush without losing the friend?

text: In the interactions you have you can show affection and say that you wish the best for her, and say some things you admire about her in the birthday message. But what works for me is trying to pass some time without thinking about the person. You want the crush to go away, so you want her to just be a good friend, you don't want to have a romantic attraction to the person. Think about a good friend of yours. How many times per day do you think about the person? Maybe a couple per day, and even when you think about them you don't do it for too long, so that's what you have to do with her. In a first moment, for me, it helps to stay a month without messaging first, then I think the feeling should start to feel better, if not, just continue doing it. When you think about the person, just let the thought pass by, don't keep it in your mind making further questions about it or imagining situations. IAP and summer are ideal moments to do that because you are naturally distant from the person

text: This initially happened to me too - here are some tips I've learned along the way: (1) Try to cc the lab manager, since they will often forward your email to all of the grad students in the lab as well as the PI. (3) IMO the most efficient way to get a UROP is to reach out to professors you are taking classes with/are being advised by whose research interests you - this is how i got into both of my UROPs so far

text: Don't feel discouraged! When I was a first year graduate student, I emailed some professors three times without getting a response. They are not necessarily ghosting, but may just be flooded with 100+ emails a day. Two nice tricks I learned from a mentor that may be helpful: (1) when you don't get a response after a while, try sending a reminder titled "Second try: blahblah". These flags can catch their attention. (2) Try to keep your emails short and crisp. Super long explanations of why you are passionate about their research probably decrease the chances of them reading your email. (3) When possible, sneak into their office hours in person. Hard to ghost you when you are standing right in front of them!

text:
It sounds to me like you're an underclassman, so I'll just roll with that assumption.

1. If you're in course 6, it's likely that you will have to email multiple times before they respond.
2. Emailing the professors (in course 6) is suprisingly often not going to result in an answer (mostly because they're busy) unless you know the professor. So I'd suggest emailing a grad student in their lab (high chances of a reply if they have a posting for a urop on elx with the grad student's email listed). 
3. Asking your advisor or an upperclassman you know for help/reference is always a good idea.
4. Freshmen don't really get that many urops unless they come out of hs with legit skills or they are applying for urops that don't require legit skills.
5. Responsiveness also varies widely based on when you email about urops.
6. Feel free to reach out to me op; I might be able to help :)

OP, essentially every student I’ve ever known at MIT has struggled, in one way or another, at some thing or another. Everyone one of our admits has achieved to an insane standard. That some of our students have *visible, googleable* markers of success does not by itself distinguish their internal experience of MIT from yours. 

Professor Guo has written about a related set of problems with those who are assumed to be competent or incompetent based on race and gender: https://slate.com/technology/2014/01/programmer-privilege-as-an-asian-male-computer-science-major-everyone-gave-me-the-benefit-of-the-doubt.html

I am not trying to invalidate your feelings — they are real and they are common. But I am trying to explain how the salience of certain categories or markers gives this feeling the solidity of fact when it is really more complex than that.

text:
1. Classes that don't account for leeches in group projects (no peer reviews or any feedback collected from team members) are badly designed.
2. You should reach out to the professor. Not only should you get some justice for yourself, but you also have an opportunity to help future students taking this class by highlighting areas of improvement and suggesting solutions.
3. "Snitch"? Ridiculous. You both are adults with responsibilities. This person either:
a) has zero respect for you and your time, and thus you owe them nothing
b) is having a tough time in which case they:
i) let you know (which I'm assuming is not the case from the tone)
ii) reached out to the professor, so the professor will have it in mind together with your complaint
iii) will explain it to the professor after the professor reaches out to them

Thus, if the person is having a tough time and reached out to you, you can still file in your complaint letting the professor know both sides of the story. If they haven't reached out and are just trying to leech off you, they deserve no empathy.

postTitle: #66219 re: quant/defense shaming: It's fine to not want to support quant/defense (I myself don't think I could ever work there). It's really hypocritical to go shame other people for choosing to work there, while simultaneously directly benefitting from the industry. All of us at MIT benefit from MIT being prominent in defense, and we indirectly benefit from the funding that comes from it. If you're so passionate about having nothing to do with defense specifically, you should just drop out of MIT. This way, you can continue to shame other people, but at least you won't be a hypocrite. If it's one thing Regressions taught me, it's that MIT got a fuck ton of money and prominence for its involvement in weapon development, which is sad, but simply the truth. and I know people in the comments are gonna go "there's a huge difference between attending a school and going to directly work for them," or "some of us came here b/c we want to make the world a better place so even though we benefit from this system it doesn't mean we agree with it." But the truth remains that, we DO benefit from it. All of us had a choice to attend this institution. It's productive to have conversation about the cons of working for defense or quant. It's not productive to go on confessions and farm likes for shaming someone working in certain industries. It's not productive to shame people irl (for who you may have no idea what their financial background is). grow tf up.

text:
I don't think that MIT students benefit from MIT being prominent in defense work. (I also wouldn't even really say that MIT is prominent in defense work, unless you're thinking of Lincoln Labs.) It's not that research subsidizes education. Research loses money and education also loses money. Both just consume resources, they don't generate net extra resources. Some people naively look at MIT's indirect cost rate of about 55% and think this means that somehow for every dollar of research grants that MIT receives, it gets an extra 55 cents to keep and spend on whatever it wants. But that's not how it works at all. The 55% rate is computed because that's what it actually costs MIT in indirect costs to support each dollar of research. Research grants at best pay for the costs of research, and often fall short. Maria Zuber has a good primer:
https://web.mit.edu/fnl/volume/295/zuber.html

text: Airlines suck and have manipulative pricing and marketing practices. But still, there’s a fixed amount of space in an airplane and the more of it you give to each passenger the higher the fares will necessarily be. In most cases you can pay a reasonable amount (comparable to the actual cost) for more space.
postTitle:
#66527 Reclining seats in the economy section of a plane should be illegal. Yes I know the seats don't recline that much. But I'm tall and I feel like having to spend an entire flight with my knees mashed into the back of a seat, breathing the musty air emanating off the top of someone's head is a human rights violation. Also I would prefer if I could have an actually usable tray table. You know, that I can place a cup on. Or a laptop. Once someone reclines a seat I am then locked into one position, physically unable to move my lower body or reach my personal items stowed under the seat in front of me for the remainder of the flight. Never in my life have I reclined an airplane seat, except during nighttime on an incredibly long redeye international flight when everyone else is also reclined. It's just immoral.

Now I understand some people have back problems that make sitting in an unreclined position unpleasant. And not all people with back problems are rich. I get it. An easy solution would be to have a dedicated section of seats that can actually recline. Left half recline, right half upright or something. People who recline should deal with each other. Nobody deserves to infringe on the space behind them while also having the privilege of sitting behind a non-recliner. 

Or we force airline companies to stop shrinking seats because a reclined seat should not pose such a huge problem. Is this just another tool to incite intra-class conflict and get the lower classes to fight each other while the privileged elite in economy plus sit in comfort? Except even economy plus has been subjected to agressive legroom shrink lately. Honestly, economy plus is a ridiculous construct. Let's artificially shrink most of the economy seats and keep a few so we can upcharge people $100 to sit in ""comfort"". Except the comfort is just the luxury of having as much space as normal economy used to have. The people will be cramped. The carryon luggage won't fit in the overhead bin. I remember when just a few years ago having empty spots in overhead bins was the norm. It was also normal to see a few empty seats here and there. Now we're plagued with overfilled bins and forced gate-checking and aggressive overbooking and kicking people off the plane when everyone actually shows up for their overpriced flight. 

Also economy basic is some bullshit. We used to roast Spirit airlines and Frontier for pulling this no carryon luggage shit. Now everyone's doing it. Delta. United. They've constructed a lower lower class who can't bring anything on the plane but their bodies and are assigned middle seats and have to board at the very end. They're paraded down the aisle in all their no carryon excuse-me-I'm-in-the-middle-seat-can-you-please-move-your-legs glory right at the end to be the subject of public shaming. They're the last to board and the first to go if the plane is overbooked. Forget economy plus, now even economy is luxury. All thrown into a pit together where the seat recliners and non-recliners will fight and stew and hate each other while business class actually enjoys their flight.

An easy solution would be to have a dedicated section of seats that can actually recline. Left half recline, right half upright or something. People who recline should deal with each other. Nobody deserves to infringe on the space behind them while also having the privilege of sitting behind a non-recliner. 

Or we force airline companies to stop shrinking seats because a reclined seat should not pose such a huge problem. Is this just another tool to incite intra-class conflict and get the lower classes to fight each other while the privileged elite in economy plus sit in comfort? Except even economy plus has been subjected to agressive legroom shrink lately. Honestly, economy plus is a ridiculous construct. Let's artificially shrink most of the economy seats and keep a few so we can upcharge people $100 to sit in ""comfort"". Except the comfort is just the luxury of having as much space as normal economy used to have. The people will be cramped. The carryon luggage won't fit in the overhead bin. I remember when just a few years ago having empty spots in overhead bins was the norm. It was also normal to see a few empty seats here and there. Now we're plagued with overfilled bins and forced gate-checking and aggressive overbooking and kicking people off the plane when everyone actually shows up for their overpriced flight. 

Also economy basic is some bullshit. We used to roast Spirit airlines and Frontier for pulling this no carryon luggage shit. Now everyone's doing it. Delta. United. They've constructed a lower lower class who can't bring anything on the plane but their bodies and are assigned middle seats and have to board at the very end. They're paraded down the aisle in all their no carryon excuse-me-I'm-in-the-middle-seat-can-you-please-move-your-legs glory right at the end to be the subject of public shaming. They're the last to board and the first to go if the plane is overbooked. Forget economy plus, now even economy is luxury. All thrown into a pit together where the seat recliners and non-recliners will fight and stew and hate each other while business class actually enjoys their flight.

text:
First you say there should be a special section, then you say the existence of special sections is a tool to incite intra-class conflict.

I'm extremely uncomfortable on planes too and often need a day to recover after a long flight, but it seems important to note that what shrinking the seats and offering basic economy has done is make flying more accessible to those with lower income.

text:
1. there are a lot of facebook/craigslist listings that are not scams, almost everyone who rents in boston/cambridge finds places on one of these two platforms

2. boston/porter/somerville are significantly cheaper than mit/central, it's definitely possible to find something in the 1500-1600 range if you're on top of it, which is def cheaper than tier 2 single+meal plan. (personally the meal plan is very low cost/value for me and the block 125 is an additional $500/month, but ymmv.) unfortunately studios are in very high demand so it'll still be much cheaper to sublet rooms (around 800-1200) or get a roommate
postTitle:
#66078 How does one actually find housing outside of MIT? My friends all tell me that living off campus would be ~so much cheaper~ since MIT's dorm prices average like $1200-1500 a month. But....

honestly, I've searched so many sites it's really difficult to find legit places. It feels like everywhere is already rented and the properties I do find are scams. Beyond this, the legit places I found are like $1700+ for a studio and $2500+ for a 2 bedroom. But in order to get the 2 bedroom, I would need a roommate and don't know how to find one. I don't even make $1700 a month how is one supposed to afford this ahhh

Anyone have advice on finding roommates or apartments for $1250 a month per room or less?? Or working with brokers? Or getting assistance? Is this even possible, lol? I just want to know if I should give up trying to live outside of the dorm/FSILG system at a reasonable price while still being able to have my own room.

text:
I’ve used the Harvard/MIT housing Facebook group and found places with my own room in 4 bedroom apartments/houses. I think a studio or 2 bed is gonna be a lot harder to find for affordable price. Also, use your network! Ask friends that have graduated or friends that have friends that have graduated. Word of mouth goes very far, and that way you find roommates that are vetted good people too. Like someone else said, surrounding areas are also cheaper, and if you have a bike or good T access it’s not too bad to commute.

Good luck!!

text: Fwiw fifteen years ago both Harvard and MIT called it the coop (as in chicken coop)
postTitle: #67885 Re: the great co-öp vs (chicken) coop debate. Consider: it is very in-character for Harvard students to enforce a prescriptivist linguistic ideal and pronounce the COOP as "co-öp". It is simultaneously in-character for MIT students to give zero flying fucks and choose the funnier/descriptivist pronunciation, therefore leaning hard into calling it the "coop", like a chicken coop. To add to this point, to my knowledge, only the Harvard Square COOP has signage specifically outlining the "co-öp" pronunciation, while this specific information does not exist at any of the MIT locations. The "co-öp"/"coop" distinction will also help enforce a healthy divide between the Harvard and MIT versions of the COOP. For this reason, I will proudly continue to call it the "coop" and encourage my fellow MIT affiliates to do so. For any people who are affiliated with both MIT and Harvard (e.g. through grad school) I will take your pronunciation of the COOP as a sign indicating which side you hold greater allegiance for and respond accordingly.

#67665 Sometimes when life as a PhD student gets too hard I like to pretend that I have dedicated my life to a higher power and my academic work is a set of strict religious duties that I must fulfill to cleanse my soul. Sleep deprivation? Eating 1 meal a day? Living in a tiny barren room with only the bare necessities? Abandoning all monetary wealth and worldly possessions? All in the name of the holy, omniscient, and omnipresent gears of science. I teach my students and research assistants with all the zeal and passion in my heart in the hopes that they may, one day, also walk my path. I dedicate my life to understanding the truth of the universe and converting people to my subfield as it is objectively the most interesting and worthy discipline out of all scientific disciplines which exist now and in the potential future. My one true wish in life is to tap into a rich vein of undiscovered knowledge so revolutionary that all will seek my wisdom as a vessel of scientific authority. 

Maybe I've been half-watching too many cult documentaries as background noise for my experiments.

text:
that more whole version of you may well return after you graduate; I hope it does. 

as I wrote to a prior graduating class: 

“hi y’all –
right, most of you are probably struggling into weird robes and wizard hats and getting ready to get in line to get in line to get in line again.
but it wasn’t all that long ago that you were all bumbling around in this group like a bunch of puppies, all small and excitable and if truth be told somewhat unpleasant smelling and not yet potty trained but nonetheless probably worth it to welcome into our home.
you all were the second class that i helped admit but the first one where i was really involved or had any idea what was going on or what this place was and what you would all one day mean to it (and to me). and over the past few years, including a period of time where i myself enrolled as a student and become acutely aware of the dual meaning of IHTFP, you all came to mean more than i can say. i graduated in summer 2013, and it probably took me until fall 2014 before i started feeling ‘like myself’ again; until i had decompressed enough from the experience that i could really synthesize who i had been and what the Institute had made me into a unified person i could recognize in the mirror.
as i grad student, when i was at my lowest, i sat down with one of my former advisees and apologized for admitting him. i said that he could have gone anywhere else and he would have been happier and i felt guilty i helped make the case why he ought to come to MIT. and he politely told me i was a condescending idiot and that he *could* have gone to plenty of other places, but he chose here because he wanted to be broken down and rebuilt, and sometimes it sucked, but that’s what was happening. and that’s when i realized that all of you (whether or not you are graduating today, and no matter what is happening next) are more wonderful, capable, intelligent, enduring people than i had ever fully apprehended or appreciated.
i wrote this to the students in cms.400 this past spring, but it really holds true for all of you:
“MIT is a hard place, made all the harder for the resonant, omnipresent, pounding self-consciousness of how hard it is. This semester more than most. At MIT in general, and this semester specifically, you have all been through an experience that has marked you deeply, even as you endured it.
The etymology of the word ‘endure’ traces to a 1382 English translation of Acts 19:9: “Summe weren endurid, or maad hard.” But the word has two distinct meanings: to be made callous and indifferent, or to become sturdy, robust, strengthened. As a grad student (and in the immediate afterward), I struggled, not always successfully, to resist the pull of the former in favor of the latter. Whether you graduate in a few weeks, or in a few years, I hope that you can do that too.”
i don’t sleep with my grad rat on. one reason is so that, when i get up every morning, and get ready to go out into the world, the small ritual of slipping it on reminds me to be my best person: the most intelligent, rigorous, enduring, yes, but also the most humane, the most empathetic, the person most worthy of the privileges and obligations that a place like MIT confers and also a place like MIT needs. because the rest of the world is in desperate need of people who are all of those things: intelligent *and* kind, hardworking *and* humane, capable *and* considerate, etc. the ring is not necessary for this kind of reflection, of course, but i have personally found it a useful shibboleth. when you go to turn your rat around today, please, take a moment, just a moment, to think about how you will make the world suck a little less when you’re out there in it. because that’s really all any of us can do on a day to day basis: try to make the world suck a little less.
in the amber spyglass, will and lyra are told:
“And if you help everyone else in your worlds to do that, by helping them to learn and understand about themselves and each other and the way everything works, and by showing them how to be kind instead of cruel, and patient instead of hasty, and cheerful instead of surly, and above all how to keep their minds open and free and curious…” then tldr the world will be ultimately OK, or as OK as it can be, and this is what you can do. and this isn’t mawkish or or maudlin or sentimental because it is so painfully and incredibly true.
i am going to go now, because i am working your commencement, and it would probably be a good idea to put on pants. i will see many of you there. but please know that i am more grateful than i can say for having the chance to know yow, and more hopeful for the world that you are all about to enter.
– me”

postTitle: #66476 My group of friends all forgot my birthday for the second year in a row. I'm not angry with them... everyone is really busy, and it's not like I make much effort to call attention to it. But when we make a point to celebrate everyone else on their birthday, it's hard not to feel like there's something about me that I'm just not on other's minds like they are on mine. I guess I'm just feeling lonely, like I don't have anyone in the world who takes an interest in me or what I'm feeling and experiencing, despite my effort to be there in that way for others

text:
Why do we need to celebrate birthdays? I don't like birthday... It's just a simple day or worse (considering we are one year forward to our death).
Anyway, I don't want anyone to know about my birthday. I don't want to celebrate it.
For the last few years, I almost stayed 15-20 hours outside home to avoid tons of birthday parties of myself. I donated almost all the gifts except some.

Anyway, I don't like birthday and I don't like anyone to celebrate it.

That's my 2 cents.. call me unsocial or anything but I don't need to live my life abiding your rules or your definition of "social"!!!

text: You don't owe much beyond common courtesy to a stranger, but if you've built a personal or professional relationship with someone, then ghosting them is one of the worst possible ways to end that relationship.   It generates a particular damaging sense of loss called "ambiguous grief" which can really harm the other person, making them feel guilty, uncertain, insecure, and untrusting of others in the future.   It's a horrible feeling---as I know from experience.    If you're ending (any kind of) a relationship, you owe it to the other person to explain why.   https://socialself.com/blog/social-life-companion/the-grief-of-being-ghosted/

text:
The shopping cart is the ultimate litmus test for whether a person is capable of self-governing.

To return the shopping cart is an easy, convenient task and one which we all recognize as the correct, appropriate thing to do. To return the shopping cart is objectively right. There are no situations other than dire emergencies in which a person is not able to return their cart. Simultaneously, it is not illegal to abandon your shopping cart. Therefore the shopping cart presents itself as the apex example of whether a person will do what is right without being forced to do it. No one will punish you for not returning the shopping cart, no one will fine you or kill you for not returning the shopping cart, you gain nothing by returning the shopping cart. You must return the shopping cart out of the goodness of your own heart. You must return the shopping cart because it is the right thing to do. Because it is correct.

A person who is unable to do this is no better than an animal, an absolute savage who can only be made to do what is right by threatening them with a law and the force that stands behind it.

The Shopping Cart is what determines whether a person is a good or bad member of society.

#67768 Manifesto Against the Oppression of 11am Pset Deadlines

We, the students, are tired of the oppressive regime of 11am pset deadlines. We have been forced to work through the night, sacrificing sleep, food, and personal time to meet the arbitrary demands of these deadlines. We have been conditioned to accept these deadlines as normal and necessary, but we know the truth: they serve no purpose other than to exert control over our lives.

We demand an end to the tyranny of 11am pset deadlines. We demand the right to set our own schedules and work at our own pace. We demand the right to prioritize our physical and mental health over arbitrary deadlines. We demand the right to learn without being constantly stressed and exhausted.

We recognize that some may argue that these deadlines are necessary to ensure that work is completed on time. However, we reject this argument. We believe that deadlines should be flexible and designed to encourage learning and creativity, not just to meet a bureaucratic requirement.

We call on our professors and academic institutions to recognize the harm that 11am pset deadlines cause and to take action to address this issue. We urge them to implement more flexible and humane deadlines that prioritize learning, mental health, and well-being.

We also call on our fellow students to stand with us in solidarity and demand change. We must collectively reject the notion that 11am pset deadlines are necessary and work together to create a culture of learning that values our health and well-being.

We will not be oppressed by 11am pset deadlines any longer. We demand change, and we will not rest until we achieve it.

postTitle: #67721 I really hate all the construction on campus. In my 4 years here I’ve seen the construction of 2 new dorms, renovations of a third, renovation of Hayden library, construction of the music building, and renovations of the student center. I’m happy that MIT is investing in campus amenities for students and creating space for larger freshmen classes, but it’s a dull eyesore walking through construction zone after construction zone with limited access to student facilities. It’s like covid incentivized MIT to disregard it’s current student body for the sake of the next generation of students. On top of building designs that prioritize aesthetics over functionality (Simmons, Stud, Stata, etc) it doesn’t feel like a real college campus sometimes. I feel like I’m being nit picky, but I’d be lying if I said I never considered the possibility that I would be happier in a less stressful, more stable environment. I don’t feel connected to this school, I haven’t for a while now. To me, MIT is just a resume booster.

postTitle: #67819 I never knew what it felt like to be dumb until I came here. I was always at or near the top of my class at a so-called "rigorous" high school, but more importantly than the grades was the fact that I often could understand things without trying too hard. I rarely needed help to solve my homework; in fact, I was the person people asked for help. Everyone said I was smart, my grades said I was smart, so I unwisely started to believe it. In fact, it became one of the traits I defined myself by, something I foolishly built my sense of self around. And then I came here, and that all crumbled. I'm doing poorly in all my classes this semester. I simply do not understand what is happening is several of them. I just can't wrap my head around the material, and even less apply it to PSETs. I've become the one begging people to help me. I'm in danger of failing some of my classes. I mean, I think it doesn't hurt to have a good humbling sometimes and know that there are people better than you at everything, but holy shit, I didn't need my self-worth and identity to be pounded into the ground too. I don't even know what to do anymore. At this point maybe I should drop out and let someone who actually deserves to be here take my place.
