postTitle:
#66479 I think I needed an actual wake-up call and I suppose I finally got it, and looking forward to the next half of my MIT career, I don’t want the same mistakes to happen again and to fully learn from my mistakes this semester and also last semester. From all of the stress and pressure of academics to living a functioning social life, I definitely have not lived up to my own expectations of myself and how I want my life and relationships to be. I utterly ruined several personal relationships in a short period of time due to my inability to control my internal turmoil and how that manifests itself in the connections that I make with other people. And to the people that I’ve wronged and found myself in rather complicated and likely irreversible situations with, I am sorry and I absolutely need to work on these flaws of mine, particularly my attachment style and anxiety, and before I damage more relationships, I want to learn more about ways of dealing with this and becoming the person who I never was before. And hopefully, in doing that, I can finally be a positive beacon that people can rely on and that I can also finally trust. Maybe then, I can finally be comfortable and happy in my own skin.
I guess in writing this I wonder about the best ways people have found to work through their mental struggles as MIT students. How have y’all dealt with your past traumas and what changes have you implemented to lead a more fulfilling life?

text:
(just to preface: i can't speak as to the gravity of what i've been through, but it would be pointless to try and compare.)

this will almost certainly read off as a cliché, but hear me out: i try and remind myself that most things happen for a reason. that we do have the capacity to learn and grow from even the worst of our afflictions. 

consider reaching out for therapy, or even someone you really trust (whether family or otherwise), and what you hear might provide you with newfound perspective on these situations—or, at the very least, something to reference yours against. i've learned a good deal about myself in conversation with those i trust.  

the one thing i will say about your situation is this: in some sense, you define your own reality, and so i feel like it would be helpful for you to align your expectations accordingly—so that they serve you more constructively, if that makes sense. 

i think it goes without saying that the resolution to all of this likely won't come to you overnight. mistakes will be made along the way. through it all, though, strive to be patient with yourself. be deliberate in how you view and treat yourself: ideally, with the care and respect you deserve.

wishing you all the best OP! ⭐️

text: Maryanna Betterly
postTitle: #66380 This is my first confession so I hope I do this right.  This goes out to the person that lost their mom after coming out to her. I am a mom, and I want you to know that you touched many of the hearts on the parents board. I don't think I will come here again as it feels a little creepy, like this should be a place for students to have a little fun and help each other through the day, not for us moms. But, I felt compelled to respond to you. I can tell you that your mom loved you and was proud of you. I can tell you that she felt that way no matter what you say or do, nothing can change that.  I can tell you that in her last moments, her only thought was that she wished she could have made things right with you too and that she could have told you that. Moms are people too and we make mistakes.  I think its not so much that we don't trust our kids or approve of our kids, its more fear, fear of them getting hurt and making decisions that would affect them for a lifetime. It doesn't make the reaction right or excusable, but sometimes our first response is just that ... fear for our kids and just wanting to protect them. I can tell you from experience that I made mistakes with my own daughter.  I wish I could take it all back, and I've tried, but she doesn't want anything to do with me.  I miss her so much, but I am still so proud of her and love her more than anything. You should know that your mom felt the same way. Even if she couldn't tell you, she loved you and was proud of you. In time, I do think she would have realized that she needs to let you live your life the way you want and that you don't necessarily need mom in the same way as you did growing up.  That's hard for us moms too. She would want you to not have regrets, to know she loves you more than anything just the way you are, and to go on and have a happy life.  She would want you to be happy.  To live your life, to the fullest, knowing in your heart she loved you, is the best way to make things right with her now.

I am a mom, and I want you to know that you touched many of the hearts on the parents board. I don't think I will come here again as it feels a little creepy, like this should be a place for students to have a little fun and help each other through the day, not for us moms. But, I felt compelled to respond to you. I can tell you that your mom loved you and was proud of you. I can tell you that she felt that way no matter what you say or do, nothing can change that.  I can tell you that in her last moments, her only thought was that she wished she could have made things right with you too and that she could have told you that. Moms are people too and we make mistakes.  I think its not so much that we don't trust our kids or approve of our kids, its more fear, fear of them getting hurt and making decisions that would affect them for a lifetime. It doesn't make the reaction right or excusable, but sometimes our first response is just that ... fear for our kids and just wanting to protect them. I can tell you from experience that I made mistakes with my own daughter.  I wish I could take it all back, and I've tried, but she doesn't want anything to do with me.  I miss her so much, but I am still so proud of her and love her more than anything. You should know that your mom felt the same way. Even if she couldn't tell you, she loved you and was proud of you. In time, I do think she would have realized that she needs to let you live your life the way you want and that you don't necessarily need mom in the same way as you did growing up.  That's hard for us moms too. She would want you to not have regrets, to know she loves you more than anything just the way you are, and to go on and have a happy life.  She would want you to be happy.  To live your life, to the fullest, knowing in your heart she loved you, is the best way to make things right with her now.

postTitle: #68037 If we are to entertain the notion of a proclivity towards the pianoforte in conjunction with a conspicuous antipathy towards the harpsichord, we must duly appraise the inherent complexities of such a mental disposition. We may, in fact, liken such an individual to a 'forte-issimo ignoramus', whose musical faculties remain largely impervious to the delicate subtleties and intricate tonalities of the plectrum-plucked perfection. Indeed, the piano's hammers, with their blunt and resolute impact upon the strings, may well appear to some as the epitome of musical force, while the harpsichord's quills, with their deft and pliant touch, may seem feeble and antiquated in comparison. But it is precisely in this contrast that we discern the true value of the harpsichord, for it is an instrument that defies the commonplace and celebrates the arcane. Its otherworldly sound, with its crystalline purity and ethereal resonance, transcends the mundane and transports the listener to a realm of sheer beauty and wonder. Alas, it is a realm that remains beyond the grasp of the 'forte-issimo ignoramus', who is doomed to languish in the aural banality of the commonplace, deaf to the celestial harmonies of the harpsichord's exquisite perfection.

postTitle:
#66341 I realized I have a strong preference for people who hate the world or have been hurt by it. People who are witty in order to hide their pain. I want to be their comfort and take care of them. I want to be their only one, a light in their dark world that they love and also care for. I hate that I grew up being praised for reading when I was just reading YA fiction in my formative years. I've created this unrealistic person in my head that I want to be with. Basically, I want the main character's damaged but beautiful love interest. 

In reality, I'm not selfless enough to care for someone because I'm so focused on my own problems, which pale in comparison and are often self-imposed. I'm self-sabotaging and preventing myself from being with good people because they don't fit this image, but I genuinely can't find myself attracted to them unless there's some way I can ""heal"" them. It's mildly toxic and I hate myself for it. 

In practice, the people I want to be with start out wanting to be with me because they see me as innocent and naive. They want to protect me from the losses and pain they endured. And I love being protected by them and giving them a shoulder to lean on and lending an ear. Those moments of bliss mean everything to me. But it never works out long term because they get frustrated that I choose to self-sabotage and create problems when there are bigger issues to deal with. When they lash out and hurt me, I retreat emotionally. This starts a cycle of hurt that can only end with us separating. But these are the only people I've been able to love. I don't know what to do.

text: The first most important step of dealing with a problem is recognizing what the problem is. You’ve already done that, so you already have a leg up. Now go to therapy so you can deal with the problem.

text:
I was the same until God changed my desires to heal on my own first — as my desire to be with someone to “heal” them was a projection of how I deeply wanted to be healed as well from my own self-sabotage, but I felt that I needed to prove it myself to “be the change I want to see” or bring into existence what I craved — so I tried to be that person to someone else before I even dealt with my self-sabotage. It’s crucial you realize that all goes well and great until the long-term of your tendency to self-sabotage. You already know what you need to work on — and after only knowing failed and toxic relationships, I’ve started my journey step-by-step with God, healthy community & support, as well as guidance from mentors — individuals and/or couples who have healthy relationships, as well as therapy. I will say therapy has been helpful in acknowledging & identifying the issues + discovering coping mechanisms — I’ve been recently dealing with PTSD + OCD-like symptoms (as my therapist identified) due to a lot of trauma in past relationships, which felt nearly impossible to overcome. I’d isolate myself and try to deal with it myself, as I thought asking for help would counteract my beliefs in my identity as one who wants to be the one to heal people. But the true changes have only been possible due to the strength & love from God (who is always with us, even in the loneliest times) + healthy, loving communities around me. I’m so ever grateful, and now taking steps towards healing, I feel so much more equipped to give & make contributions towards those seeking healing as well 😊🙏🏼 We learning and growing together

All being said, your desire to be a healer is not toxic, and is rather admirable — we need more people like you who want to pour in love, especially with all the depths of suffering in our world. But you cannot pour from an empty cup. I hope my insight offered some perspective, as I relate heavily with you. Please PM me if you’d like to talk more or meet ❤️ you got this, and God got you!

Finally, I hope you continue to seek your own healing — posting this was a brave first step — and trust me, it’s a very humbling but the most worthwhile process… and your desires may begin to change as well. (I’m growing to be attracted to people who pursue their own healing as well, so it’s not all on me to heal them — in interdependence ❤️)

text:
I've struggled with being drawn to people because i thought i could "heal" them, and in my case i found there were two main underlying causes--one of which was mostly okay, one that wasn't.

The "okay" one was, i wanted to be the person *i* had needed. It felt good to give other people the support and care that i had needed and lacked. I don't think that's a bad impulse to have--it makes for a kinder world, and is so much better than "If i had to suffer, so should everyone else". The trick, i think, is not to slip into a saviour-complex about it.

The not-okay side was, i was turned off from people who (in my estimation) didn't "need healing" from me because they made me feel insecure: What could this person possibly *want* from me, if they don't *need* me? I can't give you easy advice about how to unpack that, it's a journey; but i can say that digging into the false assumptions and insecurities that thinking was rooted in really helped me to form healthier relationships.

It's possible your underlying needs and motivations are quite different from mine, so i don't know whether you'll find any of that useful. But i'm glad you felt comfortable and confident enough to talk about it!

text:
Most MIT depts give grad students ~ 40k which is more than enough to live comfortably in Boston alone if you accept a moderate commute or roommates, and can even manage to support two people if you squeeze (how many grad students have a dependent to support entirely on their stipend anyway?)

There's plenty of organizational things MIT can do that don't cost extra money like not having grad tuition and stipend come out of grants (which makes us beholden to PIs and specific grants, or fellowships), or places where MIT can use its local power to help us (transport costs, legal/organizational help with housing), or places where MIT can collecively do for cheaper what is more expensive for each of us individually (healthcare, especially emergency expenses which can bankrupt an individual but MIT has lawyer power to contest).

But just demanding more money in a free, functional labor market shows a desire for a fight more than for solutions.

(also, reminder than "union shop" is a euphemism for "we want you to have to pay us fees even if you're not a member or don't want to be involved")

text:
i just graduated as a 6-1/8, and I've stuck around to MEng and write a bit of the curriculum for the new 6-2 core, and i'm teaching some 6-1 stuff over IAP.

you've got a point - a lot of new discoveries in physics have relied on more experimental data than ever before, with a LOT of new techniques that are oustside of the standard set of methods. being able to tastefully apply ML as well as standard methods has been a massive part of my experience. but so have the electrical skills I've gained - those have been liquid gold in experimental design and system modelling. there's a case for both a 6-1/8 and a 6-2/8, it just depends on your aim.

and don't wait for the departments to get curriculum that does what you want, go take the classes yourself! do what's interesting to you, don't wait for us to put something together for ya 🙂

dm me OP tho, am curious to hear more of your thoughts :)
postTitle: #66285 Would anyone else be interested in an update to the 6-1/8 Flex major, particularly since course 6 admin is shifting away from 6-1? I think a 6-2/8 flex would be a much more appropriate option to have, given that coding skills are necessary for a physicist in todays day and age, while EE skills aren’t.

text: OP, sounds like you're just not that interested in EE lol... what motivated me to choose 6-1/8-flex was my interest in areas like nanotechnology and quantum computing that draw on both subjects heavily. And this is just two of the COUNTLESS areas where EE and physics come together (RF, optics, semiconductors, just to name a few more). As a 6-1, the 8 classes give me a better understanding of what's going on "under the hood" while having those EE skills allows me to apply the more theoretical side of physics to something concrete-- do you know how many physicists are looking for those with EE backgrounds? 6-1/8-flex exists because of that natural overlap between the two and just how popular the combo was so a program that defines how to get the most out of both majors clearly is incredibly useful. Fortunately for you, 8-flex is specifically designed to make double majoring with 8 a little easier course load wise, so if 6-2/8 is something you're into, meet with the flex coordinator to start figuring out your courses and concentration!! At the end of the day, 6-1/8 or 6-2/8 it's still a double major and a shit ton of work regardless if the track exists or not.

postTitle: #68086 Remember kings and queens: In this life it's 1.) What it IS, 2.) What it HAS to be, 3.) What it COULD be, and 4.) What it could have BEEN. In other words: Live in the moment because the decisive actions you take now will have the strongest impact on where you end up down the road. Accept and embrace the things that you can't change and rather than dwelling on them, plan around them. Never lose sight of your dreams and look forward to moving towards them. Lastly, while you shouldn't spend too much time thinking on the past, reflection is essential. This goes both ways. Honestly evaluate what you could have done differently but don't take for granted what you've accomplished already. We're here after all so you must have done something right. Believe in yourselves, this world is ours!

#66316 I don't know how to feel right now. My mom passed away a week ago, and I can't help but feel guilty that I never got to reconcile things with her. We had a huge fight during Thanksgiving, when I came out as gay to her. She said I was emotionally abusing her, and that she couldn't accept me as I am. I had hoped that if I waited to tell her until Thanksgiving, she'd be more understanding and supportive.

But I was wrong.

I'm so angry at her for not being able to accept me, but at the same time, I feel so guilty that I never got to make things right with her. I wanted so badly for her to be proud of me and love me as her child, no matter who I am.

I never got to make things right with her, but I hope that wherever she is now, she can see that I'm proud of who I am. I hope she can look down on me with the same love and acceptance that I always wanted from her.

text:

text:
First, I think it's great you've been trying to work through your difficulties. As for your points, the research support for therapy is robust (although it's occasionally challenged in significant ways), but I don't think that evidence needs to be cited here. Even the APA itself acknowledges "psychotherapy does not work perfectly or for all clients" (https://psycnet.apa.org/doiLanding?doi=10.1037%2Fa0031817), so any trouble you've been having in finding the right support is certainly not your fault. It's possible that there's a therapist out there who could help you a lot, but it could be demoralizing for you to try to find one, especially after your bad experiences with the others. I'd like to give better advice about how you can best be supported, but that kind of feeds in to my next point: any advice I give may be inadequate, especially since I don't know you (or do I? 👀) The only thing I really feel confident recommending is seeking viewpoints from several people you trust, and making sure that you feel listened to and respected by them. One thing I will comment on, although it is personal, is that whenever I go to therapy, I'm not necessarily looking for my therapist to say anything "smart, eye opening, or useful". Sometimes I just start talking and find that I'm surprised by what I say, and what it reveals about what I believe or think. Again, it's personal, so maybe you've tried that and it hasn't worked, and that's fine - just wanted to point it out just in case.

As for your other claim about the industry as a whole, I do think it's unfortunate, and outrageous, that therapy is so expensive. Medical care in general seems to suffer from severe affordability issues. Maybe it's a supply/demand thing - given that there are so few therapists, the cost for their service is necessarily high. But I'm not an economist and I haven't given much thought to it. I would just be hesitant to generalize that all therapists want to suck you dry (OF MONEY, TO BE CLEAR), and that therapy doesn't work unless you believe it does, as you claimed. Maybe I and the other people for whom therapy is effective are just schmucks and we can feel better after talking to our friends. But somehow we don't, which is why we need therapists. And I think it's likely that the kindness showed to you by at least some of the therapists you saw was genuine, because as I understand, many therapists go into therapy and continue being therapists because they want to help people, and they know that their profession is evidence-backed. Which doesn't make it guaranteed to work, but it's as good as we can get.

text:
MIT student turned therapist! The truth is that our industry is very poorly regulated and has very low caliber training. Grad school was a cakewalk, I worked 2 full time jobs and got a 4.0 (this is not a humble brag, this is absolute sad because grad school should feel like you're being challenged and learning, not like I'm paying for a sheet of paper). I have classmates who wrote about using tarot cards in their therapy treatments and passed classes. (Tarot cards are great! Just not evidence based practice!) Our licensing exam is so easy I had friends (who have never taken a therapy course in their lives) try some questions and they would have passed (passing is like a 65% btw). I have worked with more therapists than I can name who are just flat out incompetent. And even worse, they are so so susceptible to Dunning-Kruger effect.

So no, you are not crazy. A lot of therapists are, simply put, absolutely terrible. It sucks because it leads to people believe that therapy doesn't work for them, when most of the time it's because the therapist is a horrible fit. Even worse is the amount of pseudoscience that invades our field (ask me about EMDR; actually probably best you don't).

Personally, I believe therapists in general are pretty money-hungry (there, I said it). Insurance will reimburse me $90 to see a patient for 53 minutes (here in Texas; the rates are prob higher in MA), and many therapists think they are above that. My dudes, you went to a 2 year grad school program with bargain bin QA and you don't wanna take $90/hr? Instead you see young therapists, 2-3 years out of grad school, trying to charge $180 via cash pay. Sigh. It really restricts access to treatment and I HATE it.

I could go on and on about his but I'll leave it for now. tl;dr - might not be you, might be them. Keep trying! Took me 6 years to find a therapist that worked for me!

text:
I started dating my partner 3 months before we got kicked off campus (Covid) and we had jobs on opposite coasts. We dated long distance for 2 years and then he moved across the country for me (and 3 years in, we’re now engaged). If you’re both willing to do it, the things that helped us- 1) talking about long term compatibility relatively early, because you really want to access if the pain/challenges of LDRs are worth it. 2) being crystal clear/both buying in on a timeframe for being back together (for us, 2 years was workable, and we both agreed to work out how to be together in that span). 3) work out how you‘ll stay in touch/see each other- we talked daily (thank god for FaceTime) and tried to see each other every 4-6 weeks. 

I hated the long distance relationship part but it was worth it for sure - so, if you really connect and you think you can work it through, I’d say communicate a lot /give it a go

#66135 TW: Depression

does anyone have experience with depression & cognitive decline + the effects of antidepressants on cognitive function? i've been depressed for a fair number of years and feel like my brain function has declined as a result of this. i'm hoping to get my life back together with the help of antidepressants, but i'm concerned that they might dull my brain function/creativity/thinking speed even more. any advice in general on how to reverse this is appreciated.

text: depression messes with your cognitive functioning, especially executive functioning and memory (in my experience and validated by research iirc). not being depressed will improve this greatly! I have very little memory of undergrad 5 years out, to the point of being shocked to find some classes on my transcript when I applied to grad school, because my depression wasn't sufficiently treated. (this wasn't really MIT mental health's fault - I should've been getting more treatment earlier but didn't think I needed it at the time). taking ADs is generally associated with improvement in cognitive functioning, and ECT, a treatment of last resort should you let your depression fester, definitely messes with cognition and memory. please get the treatment you need now; you won't be creative or smart if you're dead.

text:
Definitely not normal. You can only NR, not Fail :) 

In all seriousness, a lot of folks NR classes. I definitely did, and not by a close call either; I think my cumulative grade in physics was a 49. It’s okay - just retake in spring and it’ll be easier since it’s not your first pass through the material!
postTitle: #66530 Is failing classes in freshman fall normal? I thought i was failing one class and suddenly it turned out I’m failing two. I know this is a really bad sign and disappointing situation, but please someone tell me that it has happened before, I can’t stop crying.

text:
There is no "normal", everybody goes through stuff in their own way. But it's certainly not rare, and it's nothing insurmountable. I failed my share of classes, it's okay.

When you're feeling up to it, it's worth considering why it happened. Did you struggle to get your head around the course material? Did you have trouble balancing your workload, and fall behind? Were you "turned off" by the subject matter, and couldn't find the motivation to engage with it? Were the classes run in a format you haven't encountered before, and you found it difficult to adapt your learning style to the way it was being taught? There are lots of possible underlying reasons to fail a class. It's worth seeing if you can identify what went wrong, so you can learn from the experience.

Regarding the class you were "suddenly" failing: Do you mean you were doing okay, but then an assignment or exam threw you for a loop, and your grade dropped? Or do you mean that you had *thought* you were doing well, and were surprised to find out your grade wasn't as good as you thought it was? If it's the latter, it might be worth talking to the instructor to understand how that happened, and whether there's something you could do to keep from getting unpleasantly surprised like that again.
